wasm: add the ARCH_FORCE_MAX_ORDER knob (pc #139 Gate 0.2)

The NOMMU exec path (binfmt_wasm → do_mmap_private) needs ONE contiguous
buddy allocation for the whole program binary, so MAX_PAGE_ORDER is a hard
ceiling on executable size: the default order 10 = 4MB, and a real
compiler binary (clang.wasm, tens of MB) can never load. mmzone.h already
honors CONFIG_ARCH_FORCE_MAX_ORDER; arch/wasm just never exposed it.
Default stays at the kernel's own 10 — pc's build sets 15 (128MB blocks)
via scripts/config in vendor/linux-wasm/build.sh configure_kernel.

--- a/arch/wasm/Kconfig
+++ b/arch/wasm/Kconfig
@@ -122,4 +122,18 @@ config PGTABLE_LEVELS
 	int
 	default 2

+config ARCH_FORCE_MAX_ORDER
+	int "Maximum zone order"
+	range 10 17
+	default 10
+	help
+	  The kernel's buddy allocator limits all contiguous allocations to
+	  2^order pages. Without an MMU every process image is one contiguous
+	  allocation (do_mmap_private), so this bounds the size of the largest
+	  executable that can load: the default order 10 with 4KiB pages means
+	  4MiB. Raise it to run larger programs (order 15 = 128MiB blocks);
+	  the cost is deeper (mostly empty) buddy free lists.
+
+	  Keep the default if unsure.
+
 endmenu
